  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and organizations that work to combat money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) policies\n- Recommends legal and regulatory measures\n- Monitors countries' compliance\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n- Provide frameworks for international cooperation\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF)\n- Helps countries develop AML strategies\n- Provides guidance and technical assistance\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Establishes international banking regulations\n- Promotes transparency in financial transactions\n\n5. Individual Country Laws\n- Most countries have national AML laws\n- Requirements for financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandate customer identification and record-keeping\n\n6. Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- International network of financial intelligence units\n- Facilitates information sharing between countries\n\nThese laws and organizations aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained money as legitimate income and to disrupt financial crimes like drug trafficking, terrorism financing, and corruption.",
